---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ContentPage from '../components/ContentPage.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Fight Prophet Methodology | MMA Rankings, Predictions, and Model Audits"
  description="How Fight Prophet builds MMA rankings and predictions, including data inputs, scoring logic, confidence signals, model limitations, and audit workflow."
>
  <ContentPage
    eyebrow="Methodology"
    title="How Fight Prophet Builds MMA Rankings and Predictions"
    intro="Fight Prophet turns fight records into explainable rankings and probability estimates. This page documents the core ideas behind the public rankings, fighter cards, and prediction tools."
    updated="May 17, 2026"
  >
    <section>
      <h2>Data Inputs</h2>
      <p>
        The model starts with structured fight records, fighter profiles, outcomes, method
        information, weight classes, title context, and manually reviewed overrides for cases
        such as country normalization, retirements, vacancies, and unusual title situations.
        Public data can contain omissions, so the site treats every output as an estimate that
        may need correction.
      </p>
    </section>

    <div class="fp-content-grid">
      <section>
        <h2>Ranking Logic</h2>
        <p>
          Rankings reward wins, opponent quality, finishes, title stakes, defenses, streaks,
          and durability across time. Losses, inactivity, and weaker context reduce the score.
          The same engine can be read globally for an all-time board or filtered to one
          division for weight-class comparison.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Prediction Logic</h2>
        <p>
          Fight predictions compare model probability with market-implied probability and
          flag confidence only when the signal clears quality checks. A prediction is weaker
          when data is sparse, fighters are inactive, recent circumstances changed, or model
          variants disagree.
        </p>
      </section>
    </div>

    <section>
      <h2>What The Metrics Mean</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Model probability:</strong> the estimated chance of a fighter winning based on historical features.</li>
        <li><strong>Market probability:</strong> the implied chance from available price context when it is available.</li>
        <li><strong>Edge:</strong> the gap between model probability and market probability, not a guarantee.</li>
        <li><strong>Confidence:</strong> a quality label that considers agreement, data coverage, and uncertainty.</li>
        <li><strong>Calibration:</strong> whether groups of predictions win about as often as their probability says they should.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Quality Controls</h2>
      <p>
        Fight Prophet keeps historical picks and outcomes available in Fight Lab so readers
        can inspect accuracy, Brier score, log loss, calibration, and model disagreement over
        time. This audit trail matters because models can look persuasive on one card and
        still be poorly calibrated across many cards.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="fp-content-note">
      <h2>Limitations</h2>
      <p>
        MMA is noisy. Injuries, weight cuts, travel, judging variance, late replacements,
        small samples, and stylistic mismatches can overwhelm historical trends. Fight Prophet
        is for education and analysis only, never financial or betting advice.
      </p>
    </section>
  </ContentPage>
</BaseLayout>
